s); Robert Rishton, 1603, James Rushton, 1627, Robert Riston, 1757 in   IGI   (Colne, Lancs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Rushton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Rishton (Lancashire) and Rushton (Staffordshire), and perhaps also from Rushton (Cheshire, Northamptonshire), Rushton in East Stoke (Dorset), and Rhiston (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>risc</i> ‘rush’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"IGI","meanings":["1  English: (i) perhaps a variant of   Garth   with loss of  <i>-r-</i> before the final consonant. Compare Thomas Gath, 1600, John Garth, 1619 in   IGI   (Saint Keyne, Cornwall); Nicholas Gath, 1716, Thomas Garth, 1726 in   IGI   (Saint Breward, Cornwall). (ii) alternatively, a variant of   Goth   with unrounding of the vowel, if not vice versa.","2  Irish: from  <b>Mag Eochadha</b>,  see  McGough  ."]},{"name":"Riston","meanings":["English: habitational name from Long Riston (East Yorkshire), North and South Reston (Lincolnshire), and East and Sco Ruston (Norfolk). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hrīs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The name may sometimes have been confused with   Ritson  .","English: occasional variant of   Rushton  .","Scottish: habitational name from Reston in Coldingham (Berwickshire), cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRS